The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, December 15, 2003  Corporate Briefs																								 Globeop Financial Services (GFS), a provider of automated support services and risk reporting for hedge funds, is to commence operations in India. Its Mumbai office would complement their offices in New York and London, giving the company 24-hour processing capabilities and clients the ability to tap resources across three continents. The firm is actively seeking to hire chartered accountants, software engineers and others with experience in financial services.																								 Hutch has extended the international roaming services to over 100 countries through tie-ups across 226 networks in Asia, Europe, Australia, America and parts of Africa. International users can avail of roaming services in these countries and visitors from other nations can use the companys roaming services.																								 Motor Industries Co Ltd (Mico), a member of the Bosch Group, has achieved a milestone with the rollout of its 10 millionth inline fuel injection pump. German auto component major Bosch is evaluating plans to invest millions of euros in its Indian subsidiary Mico for producing electronic pumps which provide better fuel efficiency and confirm to stricter emission norms.																								 Mahindra amp; Mahindra Ltd has launched Scorpio, Bolero GLX, Bolero Double Cab, Bolero Single Cab, and MM540 at the Bologna Motor Show in Italy, marking its foray into Europe. The vehicles will be on Italian roads by end-December.																								 Uco Bank has reduced the rate of interest across its mid-market products to pass on the benefits of reduced cost of fund and revised risk perception for its customers. The bank has reduced interest rate on housing loans up to 5 years by 50 basis points to 7.5 per cent per annum, for five to 10 years by 25 basis points to 8.5 per cent and for 10 to 20 years by 50 basis points to 8.5 per cent. The interest rate on Uco Pensioner and Uco Narishakti now stands at 11 per cent.																								 The Tata Metaliks board has approved the setting up of a cokery within or near the companys plant premises in Kharagpur to meet its internal requirements. It will reduce the companys dependence on imported coke, which has seen violent fluctuation in its price globally.																								 AB Electrolux will source components worth Rs 1000 crore from India. This is in line with the companys identification of the country as a sourcing base for auto components and material for its outdoor division that makes garden and forestry equipment like chain saws, riders, lawn mowers and lawn tractors.																								 Weikfield introduces five variants of soups from Campbells kitchen. The flavours include cream of mushroom, cream style corn with mushroom, golden corn, tomato soup and mushroom potage. ADVERTISEMENT
